['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What are ability checks used for?', \"Ability checks are used when you want to do something that isn't covered by an attack roll or save.\"]\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'How do you make an ability check?', 'To make an ability check, roll a d20 and add the appropriate ability modifier.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What happens if the total of an ability check equals or exceeds the DC?', 'If the total of an ability check equals or exceeds the DC, the ability check is a success and you overcome the challenge.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What happens if the total of an ability check is less than the DC?', 'If the total of an ability check is less than the DC, the ability check is a failure and you make no progress toward the objective, or you make some progress but also suffer a setback, as determined by the GM.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What is a contest?', 'A contest is a special form of ability check that occurs when your efforts are directly opposed by someone else.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'How do you determine the winner of a contest?', 'Every participant in a contest makes an ability check. The participant with the highest check result wins the contest and either succeeds at the action or prevents other participants from succeeding.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What happens if there is a tie in a contest?', 'If there is a tie in a contest, the situation remains the same.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What is a passive check?', \"A passive check is a kind of ability check that doesn't involve any die rolls.\"]\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', \"How do you determine a character's passive score?\", \"A character's passive score is 10 + all modifiers that normally apply to the check. If the character has advantage, add 5. For disadvantage, subtract 5.\"]\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What is the benefit of working together on an ability check?', 'When two or more creatures team up on a job, the creature with the highest ability modifier is designated the lead for the effort and can make an ability check with advantage, reflecting the help given by the others.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'What are the requirements for a creature to provide help on an ability check?', 'A creature can only provide help if they have capacity to do the task and their assistance would be productive.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'Can a creature help on an ability check if they lack proficiency in the skill being used?', 'No, a creature can only help on an ability check if they have proficiency in the skill being used.']\n['THE THREE TYPES OF CHECKS', 'Can a creature help on an ability check if their assistance would not be productive?', 'No, a creature can only help on an ability check if their assistance would be productive.\\n1']\n['GROUP CHECKS', 'What is a group check?', \"When a number of individuals try to accomplish something as a group, the GM might ask for a group check, where characters who are skilled at a particular task help cover those who aren't.\"]\n['GROUP CHECKS', 'How do you make a group check?', 'Everyone in the group makes the ability check, and if at least half the members succeed (rounding up), the whole group succeeds; otherwise, the group fails.']\n['GROUP CHECKS', 'When are group checks most useful?', 'Group checks are most useful when all the characters succeed or fail as a group, such as when navigating a swamp to avoid quicksand and sinkholes.']\n['RELEVANT PROFICIENCIES', 'What are the two main types of proficiencies that can modify an ability check?', 'Tool proficiencies and skill proficiencies.']\n['TOOL PROFICIENCIES', 'What does a tool proficiency allow you to do?', 'A tool proficiency allows you to add your proficiency bonus to any ability check you make using that tool.']\n['TOOL PROFICIENCIES', 'What determines the ability modifier used for a tool check?', \"The ability modifier used for a tool check depends on what you're trying to do, 